+{"type":"message","id":"5b4a8d38","parentId":"2c289ce2","timestamp":"2026-03-28T18:42:38.864Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Operator notes for this run:\n## Operator note — 2026-03-28T18:27:01.073Z\n\nRefer to health-check/health-check.txt and address\n\nThese notes are authoritative user steering for this run. Follow them unless they directly conflict with the repository state or the controller's explicit task.\n\nParent conversation handoff summary:\nParent conversation handoff summary\nSummary model: anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5\nSource items: 265\n\nOverview:\nST6 is an enterprise software company enabling weekly commit-based planning with AI assistance. The session discussed how to make AI integral to the product (not bolted-on) and reviewed an evaluation pipeline for AI quality. We concluded the next milestone is implementing enforceable AI quality thresholds via: adding a critical field to eval cases, wiring two existing LLM judge prompts (title-quality, criteria-quality) into the PromptEvalRunner, committing the most recent eval run as a regression baseline, creating an eval-thresholds.json config, building a Node.js enforcement script that compares results against thresholds and baseline, and integrating that into CI.\n\nSettled decisions:\n- Judge thresholds must be 3-layer: deterministic gates first (schema+case pass rate), LLM judge absolute thresholds second, regression relative thresholds third.\n- Split judge thresholds by risk: high-stakes features (risk signals, insights, RAG) get stricter thresholds (faithfulness >= 0.90) than assistive features (draft, lint, suggestions) which get more permissive thresholds (faithfulness >= 0.85).\n- Deterministic thresholds are hard-gates that block CI; judge and regression thresholds initially soft-gate (report but don't block) until stable.\n- Use eval-baseline.json as regression anchor committed to the repo. When eval runs, the enforcement script compares the latest results to both the config thresholds and the baseline snapshot.\n- Judge scoring in the eval pipeline is optional: if OPENROUTER_API_KEY is not set, judge dimensions are skipped, not failed.\n- The enforcement script will be a standalone Node.js script (scripts/eval-threshold-check.js) using only Node 20 built-ins, runnable outside Gradle.\n- After step 2, the title-quality and criteria-quality judge prompts will be wired into PromptEvalRunner for draft-assist cases to produce real judge scores for calibration.\n\nConstraints / must-remember items:\n- All work is backend-test-only for steps 1-2; do not modify any main or frontend source files during those steps.\n- Java code must pass spotlessCheck (Eclipse JDT formatter).\n- PromptEvalRunner parameterized test structure must be preserved, not replaced.\n- FaithfulnessEvaluator.java (runtime judge, separate from eval pipeline) must not be modified.\n- Eval runner is @Tag(\"eval\") and excluded from normal test runs — preserve that behavior.\n- Judge scoring must be optional: skip if provider unavailable (no API key), don't fail.\n- Eval results write to backend/build/eval-results/ — keep that path.\n- Step 3 requires exactly 6 test cases marked as critical: 3 in draft-assist (draft-001, draft-004, draft-008) and 3 in commit-lint (lint-001, lint-003, lint-004).\n- Regression thresholds must be configurable via eval-thresholds.json, not hardcoded in script logic.\n\nOpen questions:\n- Should the enforcement script exit 0 or 1 when judge scores are unavailable (API key missing)? Currently plan says skip those checks and pass on deterministic, but CI teams may want a clear signal.\n- The eval-baseline.json in step 3 references an old run timestamp (2026-03-26). Should we run a fresh eval before committing baseline to ensure the cases are stable?\n- How should the enforcement script integrate with existing Gradle eval tasks — should it be invoked inside build.gradle or externally in CI?\n- Do we want the threshold config to be versioned per prompt-version (e.g., separate thresholds for commit-draft-assist-v1 vs v2), or single global thresholds for all versions of a suggestion type?\n\nUse this handoff as background context. If it conflicts with the explicit task below or the current repository state, prioritize the explicit task and repo state.\n\nPlan overview:\n{\n  \"goal\": \"Implement enforceable AI quality thresholds by: (1) adding a `critical` field to eval cases, (2) wiring the existing title-quality and criteria-quality LLM judge prompts into `PromptEvalRunner` so draft-assist cases collect real judge scores, (3) committing the most recent eval output as a regression baseline and creating an `eval-thresholds.json` config, (4) building a threshold enforcement script that reads eval results and compares against the config + baseline, (5) wiring that script into the GitLab `eval:llm-judge` job, and (6) adding unit tests for the enforcement script. The result is a pipeline where deterministic checks hard-gate, judge scores soft-gate with clear pass/fail reporting, and regressions against baseline are detected. Constraints: backend-only for steps 1-3 (no frontend modifications); Java must pass spotlessCheck; preserve existing PromptEvalRunner parameterized test structure; judge scoring is optional (skip if no OPENROUTER_API_KEY); do NOT modify FaithfulnessEvaluator.java; eval results write to backend/build/eval-results/; enforcement script is standalone Node.js (scripts/eval-threshold-check.js) using only Node 20 built-ins.\",\n  \"totalSteps\": 6,\n  \"stepTitles\": [\n    \"1. Add `critical` field to EvalCase/EvalResult and mark critical cases in fixture JSON\",\n    \"2. Wire title-quality and criteria-quality LLM judges into PromptEvalRunner for draft-assist cases\",\n    \"3. Commit the most recent eval run as baseline and create eval-thresholds.json\",\n    \"4. Build the threshold enforcement script\",\n    \"5. Split CI into two jobs: eval run (manual/allow_failure) + threshold check