+{"type":"message","id":"b2e6bd87","parentId":"88b40cba","timestamp":"2026-03-28T18:42:44.271Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_hI9aQPtNlZzvUws3INxSIpDA|fc_0c3904c89cff1b130169c821242970819a899e29421bc4f171","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Plan Health Check\nModel: anthropic/claude-opus-4-6\nVerdict: ⚠️ issues found\n\n## Summary\n\nThe plan is well-structured and covers all goal requirements with no gaps. File paths, API references, and existing code patterns are largely accurate — the plan author clearly studied the codebase. However, there is one critical execution bug: Step 6 appends `node --test scripts/__tests__/*.test.js` to the npm `test` script, but the preceding `cd backend` in the same command chain means the working directory is `backend/` when the node command runs, causing it to look for test files in the wrong directory. This will cause the `unit` requiredCheck to fail. Additionally, Step 4's type classification logic for applying `judge_high_stakes` vs `judge_assistive` thresholds is underspecified (eval results don't have an explicit type field), and the baseline contains only 18 of 52 possible cases, making regression comparisons across different population sizes ambiguous. The spotless formatting risk on Step 2's large code addition is manageable but noteworthy.\n\n## Goal Requirements Covered\n\n- ✅ Adding a `critical` field to eval cases (Step 1)\n- ✅ Wiring title-quality and criteria-quality LLM judge prompts into PromptEvalRunner for draft-assist cases (Step 2)\n- ✅ Committing most recent eval output as regression baseline (Step 3)\n- ✅ Creating eval-thresholds.json config (Step 3)\n- ✅ Building threshold enforcement script (Step 4)\n- ✅ Wiring enforcement script into GitLab eval pipeline (Step 5)\n- ✅ Adding unit tests for enforcement script (Step 6)\n- ✅ Backend-only constraint for steps 1-3\n- ✅ Java must pass spotlessCheck (build requiredCheck includes spotless)\n- ✅ Preserve existing PromptEvalRunner parameterized test structure\n- ✅ Judge scoring optional / skip if no OPENROUTER_API_KEY\n- ✅ Do NOT modify FaithfulnessEvaluator.java\n- ✅ Eval results write to backend/build/eval-results/\n- ✅ Enforcement script is standalone Node.js using only Node 20 built-ins\n- ✅ Deterministic checks hard-gate via non-allow_failure threshold-check job\n- ✅ Judge scores soft-gate with clear pass/fail reporting\n- ✅ Regression detection against baseline\n\n## Step Risk Assessment\n\n### 🟢 step-1: Add `critical` field to EvalCase/EvalResult and mark critical cases in fixture JSON — low risk\n- The plan claims Jackson 2.18.3 defaults missing primitive record fields to `false` without extra annotations. This is correct for Jackson 2.18+ record deserialization, but the ObjectMapper in PromptEvalRunner is a plain `new ObjectMapper()` (line 50), not Spring's auto-configured one. Record support is built into Jackson 2.15+ core, so this should still work, but the agent should verify.\n- The plan says 6 `new EvalResult(...)` call sites. Confirmed exactly 6 at lines 108, 170, 220, 275, 330, 377. Correct.\n\n### 🟡 step-2: Wire title-quality and criteria-quality LLM judges into PromptEvalRunner for draft-assist cases — medium risk\n- Large code addition (~80-100 lines) to PromptEvalRunner.java must pass Eclipse spotless formatter. The agent must format with `./gradlew spotlessApply` or match Eclipse conventions exactly.\n- The plan specifies judge score dimension names (`titleJudge_clarity`, `titleJudge_specificity`, etc.) but the actual judge prompt responses use keys without the prefix (`clarity`, `specificity`, etc.). The agent must correctly prepend the `titleJudge_` and `criteriaJudge_` prefixes when calling `addScore()`.\n- The `callJudge()` helper using raw `java.net.http.HttpClient` needs to construct the OpenRouter chat completions request body correctly (model, messages array with role/content). This is non-trivial and the plan doesn't show the exact request format. Agent will need to reference OpenRouter/OpenAI API docs or the existing OpenRouterAiProvider code (which is in src/main and cannot be modified but can be read).\n- The plan says to read judge prompts from classpath: `eval/judge-prompts/title-quality-judge.txt` and `eval/judge-prompts/criteria-quality-judge.txt`. These files exist at the correct paths. Confirmed.\n- Placeholder names in the plan match the actual prompt template files. `{originalTitle}`, `{suggestedTitle}`, `{chessPiece}` for title judge; `{commitTitle}`, `{chessPiece}`, `{suggestedCriteria}` for criteria judge. Confirmed.\n\n### 🟡 step-3: Commit the most recent eval run as baseline and create eval-thresholds.json — medium risk\n- The baseline file `backend/build/eval-results/eval-2026-03-26T16-33-06.574104Z.json` exists locally but is gitignored (`**/build/` in .gitignore). The agent needs to copy its content to `eval-baseline.json` at repo root, which is NOT gitignored. The file is accessible on disk but may confuse agents that check git status.\n- The baseline only contains 18 results (12 draft-assist + 6 lint). The fixture files define 52 total cases across 6 eval types. Future eval runs will have ~52 results. The regression comparison in step 4 must handle different population sizes, but step 3 doesn't call this out.\n- The thresholds config references `judge_high_stakes.applies_to: ['RISK_SIGNAL', 'TEAM_INSIGHT', 'PERSONAL_INSIGHT', 'RAG_QUERY']` and `judge_assistive.applies_to: ['COMMIT_DRAFT_ASSIST', ...]`. But the eval results don't have an explicit 'type' field — only `caseId` prefix (e.g., `draft-`, `lint-`) and `promptVersion` (e.g., `commit-draft-assist-v1`). The enforcement script (step 4) must infer type from these, which is underspecified.\n\n### 🟡 step-4: Build the threshold enforcement script — medium risk\n- The plan says to use `path.resolve(__dirname, '..')` for repo root. This works for `scripts/eval-threshold-check.js` since `__dirname` is `<repo>/scripts/`. Correct.\n- The eval result JSON does NOT have a per-result `passed` boolean field. There is only a top-level `passed` count. The plan correctly describes computing pass/fail from `schemaValid` and `checks`, but the agent must implement this rather than expecting a `passed` field.\n- Type classification for `judge_high_stakes` vs `judge_assistive` threshold application is underspecified. The `applies_to` arrays in `eval-thresholds.json` reference type names like `COMMIT_DRAFT_ASSIST` but eval results use `promptVersion: 'commit-draft-assist-v1'` or caseId prefix `draft-`. The plan doesn't specify the mapping. For the initial implementation, title/criteria judge scores only exist on draft-assist cases so global means work, but faithfulness thresholds require type splitting.\n- The baseline has 18 cases; future runs have 52. Regression checks comparing overall pass rates will compare different populations. The script should ideally compare per-caseId pass/fail for regression, but the plan describes high-level rate comparisons.\n\n### 🟢 step-5: Split CI into two jobs: eval run (manual/allow_failure) + threshold check (hard-gate), and add npm scripts — low risk\n- The plan says `eval:threshold-check` should have `rules` matching `eval:llm-judge` with `when: on_success`. In GitLab CI, with `needs: ['eval:llm-judge']` and `eval:llm-judge` being manual, the threshold-check job will be in 'created' state until the manual job completes. This is correct behavior.\n- The `node:20-bookworm` image does not have npm/node_modules from the repo. But the script uses only Node 20 built-ins (fs, path, etc.) so no `npm ci` is needed. Correct.\n- Adding `eval:run` and `eval:check` npm scripts to package.json is straightforward.\n\n### 🔴 step-6: Add unit tests for the enforcement script and verify end-to-end — high risk\n\n⚠️ **Checks will fail:** The `unit` npm script (`npm run test`) ends with `cd backend && ./gradlew test`. Appending `&& node --test scripts/__tests__/*.test.js` runs from the `backend/` directory, so the glob resolves to `backend/scripts/__tests__/*.test.js` which does not exist. The node command will fail with 'no test files found' or similar error.\n- CRITICAL: The current `test` npm script is `npm run test -w frontend -- --run && npm run test -w @weekly-commit/shared -- --run && cd backend && ./gradlew test`. After `cd backend && ./gradlew test` completes, the shell working directory is `backend/`. Appending `&& node --test scripts/__tests__/*.test.js` will resolve the glob relative to `backend/`, looking for `backend/scripts/__tests__/*.test.js` which does not exist. The `unit` requiredCheck will FAIL. Fix: must include `cd ..` before the node command, e.g., `&& cd .. && node --test scripts/__tests__/*.test.js`.\n- The test file uses `require('../eval-threshold-check.js')` to import exported functions. Step 4 must have the CommonJS exports and `require.main === module` guard working correctly for this to succeed. This is a cross-step dependency that is properly sequenced (step 4 before step 6).\n- Node 20's built-in test runner (`node:test`) uses `describe`/`it` or `test()` syntax. The agent needs to use the correct API. This is well-documented but agents sometimes confuse it with Jest.\n\n## Critical Issues (will cause failure)\n\n- 🔴 Step 6: npm `test` script `cd backend` leaves cwd in `backend/`. Appending `&& node --test scripts/__tests__/*.test.js` resolves the glob to `backend/scripts/__tests__/*.test.js` which does not exist. Must insert `&& cd ..` before the node command. The `unit` requiredCheck WILL fail as written.\n\n## Warnings (may cause problems)\n\n- 🟡 Step 4: Type classification for judge thresholds is underspecified. The `applies_to` arrays in eval-thresholds.json reference types like 'COMMIT_DRAFT_ASSIST' but eval results only have `promptVersion` ('commit-draft-assist-v1') and caseId prefix ('draft-'). Agent must infer the mapping.\n- 🟡 Step 3: The baseline `eval-2026-03-26T16-33-06.574104Z.json` only has 18 results (lint + draft-assist)